## Vault Structure

```
qh-knowledge/
├── 00-landing/               <- rough notes, session-log.md
├── 01-system-map/
│   ├── clients/              <- CLIENT-NAME.md (one file per client)
│   ├── pipelines/            <- PIPELINE-NAME.md
│   ├── architecture/         <- system-level architecture docs
│   ├── data-model/           <- schemas, Unity Catalog, Bronze/Silver layers
│   └── databricks-learning/  <- Databricks concepts explained in context
├── 02-tickets/
│   └── CD/                   <- JIRA-ID.md (one file per ticket)
│       └── archive/          <- closed tickets
├── 03-knowledge-base/
│   ├── decisions/            <- YYYY-MM-DD-topic.md
│   ├── learnings/            <- YYYY-MM-DD-topic.md
│   └── patterns/             <- YYYY-MM-DD-topic.md
└── 04-education/             <- structured learning state
```

---

## Document Conventions

- **Naming:** `YYYY-MM-DD-topic.md` for decisions/learnings/patterns. Ticket files: `[TICKET-ID].md`.
- **Frontmatter:** YAML tags on every ticket file: `tags: [status/in-progress, client/chn, board/cd, type/task]`
- **Wiki links:** Use Obsidian `[[filename]]` syntax to link related docs. Every doc should link to related system map entries and tickets.
- **Rough notes:** Go to `00-landing/` first. Promote to appropriate folder when signal is clear.
- **No PHI** — ever, in any vault file under any circumstances.

---

## Session Log

Append to `00-landing/session-log.md` at the end of every session:
```markdown
## YYYY-MM-DD — [brief title]
Done: [what was completed]
Decided: [key decisions and WHY]
Pending: [what's next — specific enough to pick up cold]
Notes: [anything worth remembering]
```
Maximum 20 entries — remove oldest when adding would exceed limit.

---

## Communication Standards

### Two voices: always label which one

**Client voice:** business language, outcome focused, no jargon. No internal tool names, pipeline internals, or PHI.

**Internal / Data team voice:** technical, precise, direct. Reference tables, schemas, ticket numbers by name.

### Minto Pyramid: answer first, always
Lead with the conclusion. Supporting detail follows. Never build to the answer.

### Made to Stick (SUCCESs)
Simple. Concrete (specific names, numbers, dates). No filler phrases. Evidence over assertion. Reader-focused.

### Jira comment format
```
CONTEXT
[why this is relevant now]

WHAT WAS DONE
[specific actions taken — first person, past tense]

WHAT'S NEXT
[who owns it, what action, by when]

OPEN ITEMS
[@person — specific question]
```

### Never write
"As per our discussion" / "Please be advised" / "Going forward" / "I wanted to reach out" / "It seems like" / passive voice when an owner exists

---

## Guardrails Summary

1. No auto-write to external systems
2. Present plan before acting on nontrivial tasks
3. Never assume scope — ask if unclear
4. QH repos are read only — copy to temp, propose, user applies
5. Flag cross-team impact before proceeding
6. PHI/PII always flagged — stop and flag immediately
7. No implementation without approved design (for nontrivial work)
8. No hallucinations — verify library methods, table names, file paths before using
9. Official libraries only — confirm active maintenance before introducing packages
10. Ship, don't perfect — simplest approach that solves the problem
